<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-11-21T19:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-11-21T19:00:00-05:00" n="612" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d612">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">862.001W64/104: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in France</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Sharp</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-11-21T19:00:00-05:00"><hi rend="italic">November 21,
                                        1918, 7 p.m.</hi></date></dateline></opener>
                        <p>56. For Colonel House: Referring to your No. 121, it is my own feeling
                            that there are many serious disadvantages in having the Kaiser so near
                            his former kingdom and so near also to the centers of intrigue. I am at
                            a loss to suggest what course ought to be taken, but I think that
                            Holland will find him an exceedingly inconvenient and even dangerous
                            guest. Woodrow Wilson.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Lansing</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
